</media>
<caption>This image illustrates the coupling of oxidation and reduction reactions. Molecule B is being oxidized to a lower energy state while molecule D is being reduced to a higher energy state. (Image by Robert Bear)</caption></figure></para><section id="fs-id2763612">
<title>Electron Carriers</title>
       <para id="fs-id1405882">In living systems, a small class of compounds functions as electron shuttles: They bind and carry high-energy electrons between compounds in pathways. The principal electron carriers we will consider are derived from the B vitamin group and are derivatives of nucleotides. These compounds can be easily reduced (that is, they accept electrons) or oxidized (they lose electrons). Nicotinamide adenine dinucleotide (NAD) (<link target-id="fig-ch07_01_01" document=""/>) is derived from vitamin B3, niacin. NAD<sup>+</sup> is the oxidized form of the molecule; NADH is the reduced form of the molecule after it has accepted two electrons and a proton (which together are the equivalent of a hydrogen atom with an extra electron).</para>
